WEBVTT

00:01.043 --> 00:02.624
ANNOUNCER:
Previously on Slasher.

00:03.463 --> 00:06.079
So I spoke to Tom Winston,
and he said he'd do it.

00:06.090 --> 00:07.170
For a lock of my hair.

00:09.802 --> 00:13.465
But if you revere the truth,
you'll do this for me.

00:14.223 --> 00:15.133
You're gonna have dinner
with me.

00:15.141 --> 00:16.506
Me and Lisa-Ann Follows.

00:16.517 --> 00:17.802
The Lisa-Ann Follows?

00:18.019 --> 00:19.850
You got a face for TV.

00:20.980 --> 00:21.935
[ Gunshot ]

00:22.773 --> 00:23.558
Hey!

00:23.774 --> 00:24.638
[ Groans]

00:24.901 --> 00:27.483
[ Screaming, groaning ]

00:28.738 --> 00:29.773
Oh, God! Ah!

00:29.780 --> 00:31.190
Is there anything
in Trent's past,

00:31.199 --> 00:32.279
something he might have done?

00:34.243 --> 00:35.278
JUNE: Trent never
imagined that--

00:35.286 --> 00:36.651
VAUGHN: What?

00:36.662 --> 00:39.404
VAUGHN: Ariel wouldn't make it?
That she'd just disappear?

00:43.127 --> 00:44.663
Have you seen her?
My daughter?

00:45.213 --> 00:46.077
Shit!

00:46.464 --> 00:47.249
What?

00:47.798 --> 00:49.379
SARAH: June was
with Trent that night.

00:49.717 --> 00:50.832
What the hell's going on, Chief?

00:51.010 --> 00:53.171
June. Her life is in danger,
so I'm bringing her in.

00:53.179 --> 00:55.716
I want every available officer
to search downtown.

00:55.723 --> 00:57.384
You find June Henry,
and you bring her back here

00:57.391 --> 00:58.255
right away.

01:00.811 --> 01:02.722
[ Gasps, struggles ]

01:26.254 --> 01:27.915
-You're saying it's not fine.
-I know, but--

01:27.922 --> 01:28.957
You know what my thing is.

01:28.965 --> 01:30.671
[ Laughs ]
I know what you think.

01:30.841 --> 01:33.457
Debbie, you know, as long as
you're happy with your camera,

01:33.469 --> 01:34.504
it's all good,

01:34.512 --> 01:36.628
but then I get to take you home,
so you make me happy, so,

01:36.639 --> 01:38.425
Mm. Yeah.
[ Laughs]

01:38.808 --> 01:41.094
Oh, listen to me again.

01:41.394 --> 01:42.509
You done with the pics?

01:42.520 --> 01:44.306
Well, I just--
I wanna get a new lens.

01:44.313 --> 01:45.814
-'Cause this one, it's not--
-I wanna take you home.

01:46.107 --> 01:47.438
I know. Just, look,
I don't know...

01:47.441 --> 01:48.396
I know, it...

01:48.401 --> 01:50.062
-As long as I, you know-
-Shh, shh, shh.

01:50.653 --> 01:53.315
Oh, I thought you already
had a picture or 20

01:53.322 --> 01:54.357
of a ruffed grouse.

01:54.574 --> 01:56.405
Well, this isn't a ruffed
grouse, Debbie,

01:56.409 --> 01:57.899
this is a sharp-tailed grouse.

01:57.910 --> 01:58.945
And there's a difference?

01:58.953 --> 02:00.784
[ Chuckles ]
The tail.

02:00.788 --> 02:01.698
Sharp-tailed?

02:02.248 --> 02:05.411
I don't know why I ever bought
that book on birds for you.

02:05.418 --> 02:06.453
You never read it.

02:06.627 --> 02:08.128
Is this one in your bird book?

02:08.296 --> 02:09.456
[Laughs]
Huh?

02:09.922 --> 02:11.332
-Come on.
-Come on.

02:11.340 --> 02:13.956
Look, I-- I read your...
lovely...

02:13.968 --> 02:14.878
[ Kisses ]
[ Chuckles ]

02:14.885 --> 02:17.877
...bird book, you know,
but I can't remember

02:17.888 --> 02:18.798
every single name.

02:18.806 --> 02:20.262
You have to, though.

02:20.266 --> 02:22.302
If you love me, you'll remember
every bird in the world.

02:22.310 --> 02:23.095
[ Growls playfully ]

02:23.269 --> 02:24.600
[ Dog barks ]

02:24.854 --> 02:26.560
-Where's Milo?
-Oh.

02:26.939 --> 02:28.315
-Where's the dog?
-Milo!

02:28.649 --> 02:29.434
[ Sighs ]

02:29.692 --> 02:31.808
Oh, let's just go get him
before some farmer

02:31.819 --> 02:33.320
shoots the little bugger.

02:33.529 --> 02:34.484
-Fine.
-He does this all the time.

02:34.655 --> 02:36.191
-Then I get to take you home.
-Then you get to take me home.

02:36.365 --> 02:37.946
Milo, where are you?

02:38.451 --> 02:39.611
Hey. There he is.

02:39.952 --> 02:41.988
-Milo! Come here! Now!
-Jesus!

02:42.163 --> 02:43.198
What did he get into this time?

02:44.206 --> 02:45.707
[ Gasps ]
Oh, God.

02:45.708 --> 02:48.245
What is...?
[ Screams ]

02:50.504 --> 02:51.960
[ Rodent squeaking ]

03:02.933 --> 03:04.673
Yeah, yeah. I'm doing okay.

03:05.853 --> 03:07.718
WOMAN: I don't know...

03:08.230 --> 03:10.095
Should we go say hi?

03:11.275 --> 03:12.811
I don't know. He seems...

03:14.153 --> 03:17.611
-He seems pretty overwhelmed.
-Yeah. I can't even imagine.

03:18.991 --> 03:20.447
-Hey, Dylan.
-DYLAN: Hey.

03:21.494 --> 03:22.984
-Hi. How are you?
-Good.

03:22.995 --> 03:24.531
-Sarah.
-Hi.

03:24.747 --> 03:26.658
-Thank you for coming.
-Of course.

03:27.917 --> 03:29.578
-Quite a turn out, huh?
-DYLAN: Hmm.

03:30.211 --> 03:31.200
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

03:31.212 --> 03:32.577
We're confident we'll find him.

03:32.588 --> 03:33.418
How's Cam?

03:34.256 --> 03:37.965
He's hanging in there. You know,
he's worried, obviously.

03:38.260 --> 03:39.636
Then, again, we're all worried.

03:39.887 --> 03:40.797
Believe you me,

03:40.805 --> 03:42.511
the big man upstairs
has heard an earful

03:42.515 --> 03:43.300
from this guy.

03:43.974 --> 03:47.262
I, um-- Honey, could you go
get us some coffee?

03:47.269 --> 03:49.180
-Yeah.
-Thanks.

03:51.565 --> 03:52.645
Listen, about last night...

03:53.859 --> 03:56.942
Yeah. Cam was upset.
And scared.

03:57.613 --> 03:59.604
He-- he didn't mean
a word of it.

03:59.615 --> 04:01.025
-Are you sure?
-Mm-hm.

04:01.200 --> 04:03.065
I move back to town,
and everyone starts dying?

04:03.577 --> 04:05.704
Sarah, no one blames you
for that.

04:06.122 --> 04:07.783
You're one of Cam's
oldest friends

04:08.249 --> 04:11.286
and right now, he needs you.

04:12.753 --> 04:15.290
Hey. Thanks for coming.

04:15.297 --> 04:16.252
MAN: So sorry...

04:16.841 --> 04:17.751
WOMAN: Nice to see you.

04:17.967 --> 04:19.878
[ Chatter ]

04:22.596 --> 04:24.382
Excuse me.

04:24.557 --> 04:26.172
Cam, can I talk to you outside?

04:26.517 --> 04:27.302
Why?

04:27.476 --> 04:31.810
Just come with me. All right?
Come with me, please. Come on.

04:39.655 --> 04:40.735
[ Door closes ]

04:51.959 --> 04:53.244
No!

04:55.129 --> 04:56.744
[ Sobs ]

05:00.426 --> 05:03.042
[ Waves gently crashing ]

05:03.053 --> 05:05.465
[ Bird squawks ]

05:06.640 --> 05:08.972
June was lying out,
exposed to the elements,

05:08.976 --> 05:10.136
but the cause of death
was most likely

05:10.311 --> 05:11.300
respiratory failure.

05:12.396 --> 05:13.602
Respiratory failure?

05:14.690 --> 05:17.523
The IV, it administered
a paralytic.

05:17.943 --> 05:19.934
June's tox screens will identify
which one.

05:21.906 --> 05:22.986
Did she suffer?

05:24.366 --> 05:27.233
Uh, death wasn't instantaneous.

05:28.037 --> 05:28.867
[ Sighs ]

05:33.584 --> 05:34.664
I wanna see her.

05:38.672 --> 05:40.082
I have to warn you, uh,

05:40.549 --> 05:42.414
June suffered a variety
of wounds.

05:42.843 --> 05:45.835
Insect stings, animal bites.

05:45.846 --> 05:46.676
Cam...

05:47.848 --> 05:48.928
Son, please.

05:48.933 --> 05:50.139
Why don't you let me do this?

05:50.142 --> 05:52.519
I wanna see what he did to her.

06:06.992 --> 06:08.778
[ Sniffs ]
CAM: It's her.

06:10.412 --> 06:11.743
That's my June.

06:17.878 --> 06:20.290
-Okay, son, why don't we...
-Just shut up.

06:20.965 --> 06:21.875
Cam...

06:21.882 --> 06:24.043
Would you just shut up?

06:27.888 --> 06:31.380
Alan. Alan. Why don't we wait
for him outside?

06:31.725 --> 06:34.512
[Cam panting ]

07:06.176 --> 07:08.337
LISA-ANN: A picture-postcard
small town.

07:08.804 --> 07:10.760
A series of bloody murders.

07:10.764 --> 07:12.846
One more gruesome than the next.

07:13.267 --> 07:15.849
Is this the latest
Hollywood blockbuster?

07:16.103 --> 07:19.561
No, this is reality
for the citizens of Waterbury.

07:20.024 --> 07:22.106
I 'm coming to you live
on location

07:22.109 --> 07:24.942
with two journalists
who are living this nightmare.

07:25.154 --> 07:27.611
Dylan Bennett, the fearless
editor-in-chief

07:27.615 --> 07:28.570
of the Waterbury Bulletin

07:28.824 --> 07:30.906
and its publisher,
Alison Sutherland.

07:31.327 --> 07:33.158
Thank you for welcoming me
to your town.

07:33.162 --> 07:34.072
Thank you for having us.

07:34.079 --> 07:36.365
Now, this latest victim,
June Henry,

07:36.373 --> 07:38.284
she was the wife
of a police deputy?

07:38.292 --> 07:40.248
Yes, and she was
having an affair

07:40.252 --> 07:42.038
with our fourth victim,
Trent McBride.

07:42.046 --> 07:43.582
LISA-ANN: Is the husband
a suspect?

07:43.589 --> 07:44.749
-No.
-Why not?

07:44.924 --> 07:46.710
You see, Lisa-Ann, these
were not crimes of passion.

07:46.926 --> 07:50.089
All the victims have a deep,
dark secret in their past.

07:50.429 --> 07:51.714
And these secrets are based

07:51.722 --> 07:53.553
on one of the deadly sins,
am I right?

07:53.557 --> 07:54.933
Yes. That is the working theory.

07:55.267 --> 07:58.054
Well, then, would you say
that this killer is a vigilante?

07:58.270 --> 07:59.851
Cleaning up your town?

08:02.566 --> 08:04.181
Uh, um-hm...

08:04.652 --> 08:06.563
You see, I'm a big believer
in justice.

08:07.112 --> 08:09.603
I'm a journalist. Our job
is to expose the truth.

08:09.615 --> 08:12.527
I don't agree
that anybody can...

08:15.371 --> 08:16.201
[ Sighs ]

08:17.289 --> 08:18.324
DYLAN: ...but these are
also, in fact...

08:18.332 --> 08:19.117
-DYLAN: ...crimes...
-He's a natural.

08:19.333 --> 08:20.664
-DYLAN: ...and whether or not...
-Yeah.

08:20.668 --> 08:21.657
DYLAN: ...the victims
deserved the punishment...

08:21.669 --> 08:23.830
-He sure is.
-...society can 't function.

08:23.837 --> 08:25.338
Imagine a scenario
where every crime

08:25.339 --> 08:26.920
that's committed against me,
for example,

08:27.216 --> 08:29.548
I go out,
and I commit an equally

08:29.551 --> 08:31.587
or-- or-- or worse,
in fact, crime.

08:31.762 --> 08:33.298
DYLAN: And whether or not
the victims deserved it--

08:33.472 --> 08:34.837
You know what?
I'm gonna get some air.

08:35.140 --> 08:36.050
Need some air?

08:36.058 --> 08:36.922
-DYLAN: ...criminal acts
are given...

08:36.934 --> 08:37.889
-DYLAN: ...a carte blanche--
-Yeah.

08:37.893 --> 08:38.723
Excuse me.

08:38.936 --> 08:40.051
-DYLAN: ...on occasion...
-Su re.

08:40.270 --> 08:41.259
DYLAN: ...the criminal justice
system may or may not

08:41.271 --> 08:42.056
get it right.

08:42.231 --> 08:43.061
[ Door buzzes open ]

08:56.036 --> 08:57.025
[ Fastening handcuffs ]

09:01.041 --> 09:03.157
[ Door shuts ]

09:04.211 --> 09:06.076
Is there any news?
Did they reply?

09:06.588 --> 09:09.830
"Hey, Alan, how was your day?
What's that?

09:09.842 --> 09:11.207
You spent it consoling your son

09:11.218 --> 09:13.049
after his wife
was found in a field

09:13.053 --> 09:15.044
half-eaten by wild animals
and a Shepherd mix?

09:15.055 --> 09:15.965
Well, that's shitty."

09:15.973 --> 09:16.837
Okay!

09:17.641 --> 09:19.222
It's wonderful
to see you again, Alan.

09:20.060 --> 09:21.345
Better?

09:27.026 --> 09:28.732
[ Chains rattling ]

09:29.361 --> 09:31.226
This doesn't change anything.

09:47.963 --> 09:49.043
[ Strikes table ]

09:49.673 --> 09:51.004
I'd like to go back
to my cell now.

09:51.008 --> 09:52.123
[ Door buzzes open ]

09:57.347 --> 09:59.429
[ Chains rattling ]

09:59.600 --> 10:00.385
[ Sighs ]

10:00.976 --> 10:01.965
Okay, you're-- Sorry--

10:01.977 --> 10:03.262
your standing
this close to me,

10:03.270 --> 10:04.385
it's actually making me hotter.

10:04.563 --> 10:05.928
Your makeup's running
into your eyes.

10:05.939 --> 10:07.395
I know. I can--
I can feel them stinging.

10:07.816 --> 10:09.192
Thank you.

10:09.193 --> 10:10.399
-[ Clears throat ]
-Are you okay?

10:11.278 --> 10:12.233
Never been better.

10:12.488 --> 10:14.524
You can talk, you know,
when she asks us questions.

10:14.698 --> 10:16.279
Oh, I would, but you're kinda
sucking all the oxygen

10:16.283 --> 10:17.819
out of the room.

10:18.368 --> 10:21.326
Dylan, you are doing great.
The camera adores you.

10:21.330 --> 10:22.410
Just keep doing
what you're doing.

10:22.414 --> 10:23.324
Okay, thanks.

10:23.332 --> 10:24.117
[ Sighs ]

10:24.416 --> 10:27.408
What, we're back in five.
You wanna do something?

10:27.628 --> 10:28.788
Your job, maybe?

10:29.338 --> 10:29.997
[ Sighs ]

10:30.714 --> 10:33.126
Alan was working the room
like he was running for office.

10:33.509 --> 10:34.589
It was bizarre.

10:34.927 --> 10:37.339
Okay, so...

10:38.806 --> 10:41.798
Alan finds out that June and
Trent are cuckolding his son,

10:41.809 --> 10:44.016
and he kills them.

10:44.728 --> 10:45.592
Maybe, but...

10:46.146 --> 10:50.105
you know, they were
both guilty of sloth, so...

10:50.859 --> 10:53.236
Unless Alan's using the seven
deadly sins as a cover,

10:53.237 --> 10:54.317
but...

10:55.114 --> 10:57.105
then why would he kill
my grandmother and Justin?

10:57.116 --> 10:59.448
Yeah, right, why would
a Christian zealot wanna

10:59.451 --> 11:00.406
kill a gay Muslim?

11:00.661 --> 11:02.151
And Verna McBride?
I mean--

11:02.162 --> 11:03.823
Oh, I wanted to kill
Verna McBride.

11:04.039 --> 11:05.074
Many times.

11:05.374 --> 11:07.615
No, wait. Alan lives with Cam.

11:08.085 --> 11:10.417
The police went through that
house top to bottom.

11:10.420 --> 11:12.001
They would've found something.

11:13.257 --> 11:15.088
What about Alan's other house?

11:22.224 --> 11:23.054
Need a ride?

11:23.475 --> 11:24.260
[ Door closes ]

11:26.562 --> 11:27.347
No.

11:28.272 --> 11:30.103
I'm fine.
I'll see you tomorrow.

11:30.357 --> 11:32.689
[ Crickets chirping ]

11:51.753 --> 11:53.960
What if-- What if Alan
catches us here?

11:54.214 --> 11:55.294
I don't know—- We...

11:55.841 --> 11:57.377
tell him we're praying
for loved ones

11:57.384 --> 11:59.090
or... lighting a candle.

11:59.094 --> 12:01.335
Whatever it is people do here.
Stop worrying.

12:01.763 --> 12:02.969
Me? Stop worrying?

12:03.432 --> 12:05.514
I had an ulcer by the time
I was 10 years old.

12:06.560 --> 12:09.176
-Go, go, go. Go, go, go.
-What are you doing?

12:32.044 --> 12:33.625
ROBIN: Sarah, I don't think
anything's in here.

12:33.629 --> 12:34.664
I think we should go.

12:34.880 --> 12:37.462
Robin, please.
Just-- just look.

12:38.258 --> 12:40.465
We're wasting our time.

12:42.512 --> 12:43.763
[ Drawer squeaks ]

12:45.432 --> 12:46.467
[ Sighs ]

12:50.270 --> 12:51.180
[ Drawer squeaks ]

12:52.397 --> 12:53.386
Sorry.

13:22.052 --> 13:22.962
Robin?

13:24.263 --> 13:25.048
What?

13:38.402 --> 13:39.892
What is that?

13:41.905 --> 13:43.736
I think it's the murder kit.

13:53.458 --> 13:55.198
[ Phone chimes ]

14:00.966 --> 14:02.046
[ Birds chirping ]

14:04.011 --> 14:05.876
I-- I kept telling June
we should...

14:06.596 --> 14:09.963
you know, get one of those,
cup things, but...

14:11.268 --> 14:14.601
she said they were bad
for the environment, so...

14:17.607 --> 14:21.065
You're stuck with my swamp mud.

14:27.993 --> 14:29.984
You're not here for the coffee.

14:33.248 --> 14:36.411
How well does your dad
know Tom Winston?

14:39.421 --> 14:40.877
Why?

14:41.548 --> 14:43.960
He's his religious counselor.

14:45.302 --> 14:47.258
Why don't you get
to your point, Sarah?

14:47.971 --> 14:50.383
What if Tom's behind
the killings?

14:51.850 --> 14:54.592
He's orchestrating them
from behind bars?

14:56.521 --> 14:59.228
Having someone...

14:59.775 --> 15:01.015
carry them out?

15:01.526 --> 15:03.357
[ Birds chirping ]

15:04.196 --> 15:06.528
Found a--

15:08.784 --> 15:11.571
a murder kit
in your dad's office.

15:12.954 --> 15:16.697
Had... rope and handcuffs
and weapons.

15:17.042 --> 15:18.202
Hm.

15:18.627 --> 15:20.709
Just, I know this is
the last thing

15:20.712 --> 15:22.873
you wanna hear,
but, you know, just...

15:23.215 --> 15:26.423
take a step back, okay?
Everyone's a suspect.

15:27.511 --> 15:29.547
Yeah. Yeah, they are.

15:29.554 --> 15:32.261
Including you, Sarah.

15:32.265 --> 15:33.880
Come on.

15:34.059 --> 15:36.596
Your parents are murdered
by a religious zealot.

15:37.813 --> 15:41.146
You move back to town,
into the exact same house,

15:42.359 --> 15:43.895
and the killings start
all over again?

15:43.902 --> 15:46.860
Day after you return?

15:49.157 --> 15:50.146
Or, hey...

15:52.953 --> 15:55.444
Maybe Dylan's the killer.

15:55.831 --> 15:56.695
Hm?

15:57.624 --> 15:59.615
I mean, why would
a big city journalist

15:59.918 --> 16:03.001
move back to this
podunk backwater?

16:03.004 --> 16:06.496
And don't say so he could be
the editor of that bullshit rag.

16:06.925 --> 16:07.675
Huh?

16:08.051 --> 16:09.507
He's back here and suddenly
the killings start

16:09.511 --> 16:10.421
all over again and...

16:10.429 --> 16:11.214
[ Slams hand ]

16:11.471 --> 16:13.712
Why, he's sitting on the biggest
news story in the country.

16:14.141 --> 16:17.224
All right, well, maybe
you're the killer, Cam.

16:17.227 --> 16:19.388
Your wife was cheating on you,
so you kill her

16:19.563 --> 16:21.599
and her lover, horribly,
brutally.

16:24.192 --> 16:24.977
Yeah.

16:27.154 --> 16:30.191
Yeah. Maybe it's me.

16:36.079 --> 16:38.115
Your dad is hiding something.

16:39.458 --> 16:40.243
Yeah.

16:40.876 --> 16:42.616
Dylan is too.

16:44.212 --> 16:46.248
I'll bet my life on it.

16:46.715 --> 16:48.251
Hello, hello.

16:48.258 --> 16:49.213
[ Phone ringing ]

16:49.551 --> 16:50.666
Hey, there.

16:51.428 --> 16:55.137
A little jolt of caffeine
to start your morning. Voila.

16:55.474 --> 16:57.715
My morning started
three hours ago.

16:59.686 --> 17:00.596
Okay.

17:00.604 --> 17:03.391
I may have taken a couple of
acting classes in university.

17:03.398 --> 17:05.138
I'm pretty comfortable
in front of the camera.

17:05.859 --> 17:07.224
What, are you saying I'm not?

17:07.861 --> 17:09.852
Yeah. That's what I'm saying.

17:09.863 --> 17:13.401
Finally, some truth out of you.
I wasn't un-- uncomfortable.

17:13.408 --> 17:15.364
I- I- I bombed.

17:16.036 --> 17:18.197
Yeah. Yeah.
Big, big huge bomb.

17:18.205 --> 17:20.446
Listen, I can help you out.
Okay?

17:20.624 --> 17:22.034
I can give you some pointers
if you want. We can...

17:22.209 --> 17:23.574
What? Why would you do that?

17:24.044 --> 17:26.376
Because we're partners.
We work together.

17:26.379 --> 17:27.289
Oh, right. Okay,

17:27.297 --> 17:28.207
DYLAN: A little newspaper
called The Bulletin.

17:28.215 --> 17:30.331
You get to be charming
and telegenic and famous

17:30.550 --> 17:33.212
while I... do all the grunt work
and dig up the actual news.

17:33.220 --> 17:34.460
That's-- that's-- that's fair.

17:34.679 --> 17:36.544
Why? Did you find something?

17:37.891 --> 17:38.755
Thanks for the latte.

17:38.934 --> 17:39.844
Alison?

17:39.851 --> 17:42.558
I'm sure you've got a ton
of fan mail to get to.

17:42.729 --> 17:45.186
Okay, listen. I just did my job
last night. Okay?

17:45.732 --> 17:47.723
And I'm trying to do my job
right now.

17:47.734 --> 17:49.645
You're the one who crashed
and burned, not me.

17:49.653 --> 17:51.814
So... as the editor-in-chief,
if you found something,

17:51.821 --> 17:52.651
I need to know.

17:56.535 --> 17:57.320
Go ahead.

18:04.000 --> 18:05.865
Tell me you are not trying
to hack into

18:06.044 --> 18:07.250
June's text messages.

18:07.462 --> 18:10.579
Uh, I am trying to,
and I am failing.

18:10.799 --> 18:11.709
Good. Good.

18:11.716 --> 18:12.626
I'm glad you're failing,

18:12.634 --> 18:15.626
because it's unethical,
and it's very illegal.

18:16.638 --> 18:18.879
Okay, if you have a problem
with it, then--

18:19.057 --> 18:20.718
then you cover
the jazz cruise.

18:20.725 --> 18:22.340
I hear the boat departs
from the Main Street marina

18:22.352 --> 18:23.637
-...at noon.
- They could shut us down.

18:23.645 --> 18:24.885
They could--
they could throw us in jail.

18:25.063 --> 18:26.894
Yeah, and we could also find
all those sweet nothings

18:27.065 --> 18:28.350
that June and Trent blasted
to each other

18:28.358 --> 18:29.814
-across the ether.
-No, no, no, no.

18:29.818 --> 18:31.854
Imagine what Lisa-Ann
would give for a little sex

18:31.861 --> 18:32.896
to go with all those
blood and guts.

18:32.904 --> 18:34.735
The woman would crucify us.

18:34.990 --> 18:38.323
I have never named a source.
I'm not about to start now.

18:42.872 --> 18:44.487
You've tried
all the obvious passwords?

18:51.131 --> 18:52.120
Hello, Sarah.

18:53.341 --> 18:56.959
Taken far too long to drop by
and check out your gallery.

18:57.429 --> 18:58.339
Wow.

18:59.139 --> 19:00.970
You've really transformed
the place.

19:01.600 --> 19:02.635
Thank you.

19:06.313 --> 19:07.894
So.

19:09.482 --> 19:13.771
An old woman goes to confession
and she says to her priest,

19:14.487 --> 19:16.023
"Father,

19:16.031 --> 19:19.444
I've spoken ill of my neighbor,
and I seek forgiveness."

19:20.785 --> 19:22.696
"Go find a chicken," he says.

19:23.496 --> 19:26.203
"And pluck out all the feathers
and drop them around town.

19:26.207 --> 19:28.949
That is your penance."

19:30.962 --> 19:32.463
She does as she's told.

19:32.922 --> 19:35.709
But she doesn't feel any better
so she goes back to the priest.

19:36.217 --> 19:37.127
And he says,

19:37.636 --> 19:39.843
"Now go around and retrieve
all the feathers."

19:40.388 --> 19:41.639
And she says,
"Father, how can I?

19:42.140 --> 19:43.971
They've been scattered
to the winds."

19:44.643 --> 19:46.099
And the priest smiles...

19:47.687 --> 19:48.642
and he says,

19:48.647 --> 19:50.387
"Just like your words.

19:50.815 --> 19:53.727
What you throw out
can never be taken back."

20:02.243 --> 20:03.779
Can I help you with something?

20:03.787 --> 20:05.903
Yeah, you can start
by not upsetting my son.

20:05.914 --> 20:07.370
I could go to Chief Vaughn
with what you've done.

20:07.374 --> 20:08.329
Then, why don't you?

20:11.795 --> 20:13.251
You're jumping
to conclusions here.

20:13.713 --> 20:14.498
Am I?

20:14.964 --> 20:16.579
And you should be careful.

20:19.427 --> 20:20.803
I will.

20:21.680 --> 20:23.341
Now, thanks for stopping by.

20:29.062 --> 20:32.771
You know, your parents,
they were quite na'ive.

20:33.608 --> 20:35.394
They thought
they were invincible.

20:36.903 --> 20:39.770
I would hate to see history
repeat itself.

21:19.696 --> 21:21.061
This one has to be my favorite.

21:21.364 --> 21:23.104
"I want all of it, Trent.

21:23.116 --> 21:25.072
I want the fights
and the makeups.

21:25.076 --> 21:27.112
I want the kisses good night
and the waking up

21:27.120 --> 21:29.361
the next morning
in your strong arms.

21:29.581 --> 21:32.823
I wanna walk along the beach
with you at Catherine Cove,

21:32.834 --> 21:35.746
the sand between our toes
just you and me,

21:36.129 --> 21:38.415
[ Laughs ]
and the sunset.

21:38.423 --> 21:41.756
I wanna kiss you
and call you 'baby'.

21:42.093 --> 21:44.960
That's what I want, Trent.
With you."

21:45.597 --> 21:48.009
She sounds like an oxygen
deprived teenager.

21:48.016 --> 21:51.349
How... did you get these?
They are gold.

21:52.145 --> 21:53.726
Uh, they were e-mailed to us.

21:54.063 --> 21:56.019
We can't reveal our source,
obviously.

21:56.024 --> 21:56.934
Yeah.

21:56.941 --> 21:57.930
Was it June's husband?

21:57.942 --> 21:58.772
[ Chuckles ]

21:58.943 --> 22:00.774
Or one of Trent's
ex-girlfriends?

22:00.779 --> 22:03.486
We could bring her on the show,
add a little "zhuzh".

22:03.656 --> 22:05.783
Like I said, we can't reveal
our source.

22:05.784 --> 22:06.944
You understand.

22:07.869 --> 22:11.032
All right, well, tonight,
our focus is sex, sex, sex.

22:11.372 --> 22:12.361
Are you okay with that, Dylan?

22:12.582 --> 22:14.038
DYLAN: Yeah, um,
that is the story.

22:14.042 --> 22:15.748
Uh, right?
Alison, you want to--?

22:15.919 --> 22:17.455
Of course, of course.
I mean, if we can...

22:17.879 --> 22:19.335
...publish it,
we can talk about it.

22:19.589 --> 22:22.296
Actually, it might be better
if we just focus on one of you.

22:22.467 --> 22:24.128
I mean, it's easier
for our audience.

22:24.302 --> 22:26.293
You know, keeps their attention.
You understand what I'm saying.

22:26.513 --> 22:29.175
Yeah, I mean, but Alison
is the face of The Bulletin.

22:29.766 --> 22:31.131
Yeah, but The Bulletin will
still get a prominent

22:31.309 --> 22:32.970
display in the chyron.

22:33.228 --> 22:35.389
Well, it's, um, it's your show.

22:35.396 --> 22:38.183
So if that's what you think
is best, then--

22:38.399 --> 22:39.525
Great. I knew you'd understand.

22:39.526 --> 22:40.436
Yeah, but wait.

22:40.443 --> 22:42.479
Um, the texts are salacious,
absolutely, but I,

22:42.862 --> 22:45.774
you know, I feel like
it's really a love story

22:46.074 --> 22:47.063
between a man and a woman.

22:47.325 --> 22:48.690
Now, I can give
the male perspective,

22:48.701 --> 22:50.487
and I think Alison would be
great giving the, uh, female...

22:50.662 --> 22:51.697
-...point of view.
-Well, let me think on it.

22:51.996 --> 22:53.827
I hear what you're saying.

22:54.123 --> 22:55.909
Great work today.
See you tonight.

22:56.334 --> 22:57.119
It'll be fine.

22:57.335 --> 22:58.085
Hey, hon.

22:58.336 --> 23:00.076
Those texts were personal,
not news.

23:00.338 --> 23:01.202
Sarah, I--

23:01.214 --> 23:02.124
Did you think about Cam?

23:02.131 --> 23:03.462
Did you think about
what it'll be like for him

23:03.466 --> 23:04.706
when the whole town
reads this crap?

23:04.717 --> 23:07.003
Listen, I report the news,
good or bad.

23:07.011 --> 23:07.841
You know that.

23:08.847 --> 23:10.428
I do now.

23:24.737 --> 23:28.605
"Making love to Cam is like
going for a bad massage.

23:28.783 --> 23:31.149
A lot of touching,
a lot of squeezing,

23:31.160 --> 23:34.778
and you end up feeling sore
and kind of embarrassed. "

23:35.373 --> 23:36.158
Ouch.

23:36.833 --> 23:39.119
And you're telling me Cam Henry
is not a suspect?

23:39.294 --> 23:41.000
Cam Henry is a respected member

23:41.004 --> 23:42.710
of the Waterbury
Police Department.

23:42.881 --> 23:45.293
John Wayne Gacy dressed up
as a clown

23:45.300 --> 23:46.665
and performed at children's
birthday parties.

23:46.676 --> 23:47.586
Means nada.

23:47.594 --> 23:49.050
Does this look bad
for Sergeant Henry?

23:49.053 --> 23:50.088
Absolutely.

23:50.096 --> 23:51.461
But we have to remember,
Lisa-Ann,

23:51.472 --> 23:52.757
these murders are motivated

23:52.765 --> 23:55.017
by the seven deadly sins,
and last time I checked,

23:55.184 --> 23:57.641
screwing around on your husband
is not one of them.

23:57.645 --> 23:58.725
Lust is.

23:58.730 --> 24:00.766
Yep, but given how Trent
McBride and June Henry

24:00.773 --> 24:02.274
were murdered, coupled with

24:02.275 --> 24:03.856
the fact that they shirked off
their responsibility

24:04.277 --> 24:07.064
in protecting Ariel Peterson...

24:07.238 --> 24:09.615
LISA-ANN: Lust, sloth,
why can't it be both?

24:09.616 --> 24:11.231
Kill two birds with one stone.

24:11.242 --> 24:14.655
Except... he enjoys
killing people.

24:14.996 --> 24:16.532
No, really? He does?

24:16.915 --> 24:17.950
Knock me out with a feather.

24:18.166 --> 24:19.747
I think what Alison 's trying
to say is that...

24:20.418 --> 24:22.454
The Executioner's not concerned
with being economical..

24:23.046 --> 24:24.411
with his killings.

24:24.422 --> 24:25.958
LISA-ANN: Well, that brings up
the key question I have.

24:26.132 --> 24:27.838
What does this killer want?

24:27.842 --> 24:29.298
Why is he doing this?
Thoughts?

24:29.469 --> 24:30.675
DYLAN: Well, I feel like
the religious nature

24:30.678 --> 24:32.259
of these crimes
can 't be ignored.

24:32.513 --> 24:33.923
"My God is a vengeful God. "

24:34.265 --> 24:36.005
LISA-ANN: Jesus also says,
"Turn the other cheek. "

24:36.267 --> 24:37.177
In the New Testament.

24:37.185 --> 24:39.676
But I feel like this killer...

24:40.813 --> 24:42.553
LISA-ANN: Very good point,
Dylan. People forget,

24:42.857 --> 24:45.519
there are two sides
to Christianity...

24:46.361 --> 24:49.569
Why don't we ask
The Executioner himself?

24:52.241 --> 24:53.151
Serial killers...

24:53.493 --> 24:55.449
write to newspapers
all the time.

24:55.912 --> 24:58.494
Uh, The Son of Sam, BTK,
The Zodiac.

24:59.624 --> 25:01.660
If The Executioner
has a message,

25:02.001 --> 25:03.286
then please talk to me.

25:04.003 --> 25:06.039
Let me interview you.
One on one.

25:08.132 --> 25:11.295
We'll be right back to talk more
about the religious aspects

25:11.469 --> 25:12.675
of these terrible crimes.

25:12.971 --> 25:14.836
[ Show outro music plays ]

25:15.014 --> 25:16.675
MAN: And we're clear, everybody.

25:16.683 --> 25:18.924
Alison, this guy's
not done killing.

25:18.935 --> 25:20.675
He has three more to go:
pride, lust, greed,

25:20.687 --> 25:22.348
and call me crazy, but
throwing yourself to the lions

25:22.522 --> 25:23.637
does seem a little prideful.

25:24.357 --> 25:26.894
Are you concerned,
or are you just jealous

25:26.901 --> 25:28.107
that you didn't think
of it first?

25:28.111 --> 25:29.066
Jealous?

25:29.821 --> 25:31.231
He's a cold-blooded killer.

25:31.489 --> 25:32.239
He is.

25:32.657 --> 25:33.487
And, uh,

25:34.325 --> 25:36.941
that'll make for an incredible
interview, won't it?

25:40.665 --> 25:41.450
[ Sighs ]

25:42.000 --> 25:43.706
[ Crickets chirping ]

25:45.837 --> 25:46.701
[ Dog growls ]

25:50.216 --> 25:51.171
DISTORTED VOICE: Alison.

25:58.057 --> 25:59.342
Alison.

26:02.437 --> 26:04.223
[ Gasps ]

26:16.701 --> 26:18.942
DISTORTED VOICE: Open it.

26:44.479 --> 26:46.765
[ Birds chirping ]

26:47.690 --> 26:48.805
They're stored in Evidence.

26:48.983 --> 26:51.144
I understand. I'm not asking
for the originals,

26:51.152 --> 26:52.688
just some copies.

26:53.821 --> 26:54.731
Why?

26:54.739 --> 26:57.196
So you can watch dear old Mom
screw a bunch of strangers?

26:57.867 --> 26:59.653
I gave those tapes to you
in good faith.

27:00.119 --> 27:01.529
I found them in my house.

27:01.996 --> 27:03.361
My hands are tied.

27:04.165 --> 27:05.996
You know, you're not the boss
of this town, Chief Vaughn.

27:06.209 --> 27:07.870
And you're not Nancy Drew.

27:08.628 --> 27:10.744
You're a failed artist
who's stuck in a small town

27:10.755 --> 27:12.461
who can't even sell other
people's art work.

27:12.882 --> 27:14.292
That's who you are, Sarah.

27:14.592 --> 27:16.799
[ Office chatter ]

27:26.270 --> 27:27.476
[ Sighs ]

27:31.109 --> 27:32.224
[ Camera beeps ]

27:32.944 --> 27:33.933
[ Sighs ]

27:34.278 --> 27:35.688
[ Sharp noise ]
[ Flapping wings ]

27:36.864 --> 27:39.025
[ Wind picking up ]

27:42.537 --> 27:43.617
[ Camera beeping ]

27:49.168 --> 27:49.953
[ Sighs ]

27:51.754 --> 27:52.584
[ Sniffs ]

28:00.429 --> 28:02.215
[ Metal door clangs ]

28:04.517 --> 28:07.054
[ Heavy muffled breathing ]

28:14.485 --> 28:16.350
How do I know you're--
you're really him?

28:16.737 --> 28:18.273
[ Wind howls ]

28:18.447 --> 28:20.438
This could be a really
sick joke.

28:27.206 --> 28:30.619
June Henry's toxicology report

28:31.794 --> 28:35.412
will show curare
in her system.

28:37.091 --> 28:39.047
It's a paralytic...

28:40.011 --> 28:41.000
and it...

28:41.554 --> 28:45.342
left her... defenseless.

28:48.352 --> 28:50.013
Would you like to...

28:50.396 --> 28:54.139
confirm this
before we proceed?

28:56.319 --> 28:58.480
I'll take your word for it.

28:59.780 --> 29:01.691
EXECUTIONER: We all sin.

29:03.784 --> 29:08.118
Every day of our lives, we sin.

29:08.789 --> 29:10.916
Taking the Lord's name in vain.

29:11.417 --> 29:14.079
That's a sin everyone commits.

29:15.254 --> 29:18.417
However, I only kill those
who deserve to die.

29:18.799 --> 29:22.542
Even if God himself commanded,
"Thou shalt not kill"?

29:23.429 --> 29:25.670
Thou shalt not kill
the innocent.

29:27.892 --> 29:31.601
My victims... were not innocent.

29:32.230 --> 29:34.846
Does that strike a bell
with you, Alison?

29:35.024 --> 29:36.264
Of course it does.

29:37.193 --> 29:38.308
You're killing people.

29:38.319 --> 29:40.526
You've made yourself
judge and jury.

29:41.989 --> 29:46.904
I... am but a reaction
to their sins.

29:47.495 --> 29:51.909
In fact, you and I have
much in common.

29:51.916 --> 29:54.248
I'm sure-- I'd s-- I'm not sure
I'd agree with that.

29:56.879 --> 30:00.121
You're a newsmaker. Hm?

30:01.092 --> 30:04.334
Does it not perform
the duties of...

30:04.345 --> 30:07.212
judge and jury in its own way?

30:07.390 --> 30:09.802
We report the truth, the facts.

30:15.773 --> 30:17.274
Yes.

30:19.652 --> 30:22.189
[ Heavy breathing ]

30:22.488 --> 30:26.481
So help you God...

30:30.204 --> 30:31.660
[ Chuckles ]

30:31.956 --> 30:33.947
[ Heavy breathing ]

30:52.435 --> 30:55.518
Thank you for the interview.

30:58.607 --> 31:02.316
You have no sins, Alison?

31:03.738 --> 31:08.607
Nothing that weighs heavily
on your conscience?

31:11.078 --> 31:12.693
No, nothing.

31:13.164 --> 31:16.577
[ Heavy breathing ]

31:28.429 --> 31:31.262
[ Door clangs ]

31:39.523 --> 31:44.233
[ Gasps, exhales in relief ]

31:49.492 --> 31:53.201
Verna McBride put up
quite a fight.

31:54.038 --> 31:55.073
Trust me,

31:55.539 --> 31:59.873
I was far more fair with her
than she was with her husband.

32:00.961 --> 32:02.917
ALISON: Why did you cut off
her hands and feet?

32:04.173 --> 32:08.667
The plan was to chop her up
into seven pieces.

32:09.637 --> 32:13.755
I thought it would be poetic.
But I was interrupted.

32:15.226 --> 32:16.762
Holy shit.

32:16.769 --> 32:18.305
Okay, let's-- let's pump
the brakes here.

32:18.312 --> 32:20.223
Can we confirm that that's him?

32:20.481 --> 32:21.812
That could be anybody
in the mask.

32:21.816 --> 32:23.431
You heard what he told me.

32:23.442 --> 32:25.524
Stuff only The Executioner
would know.

32:25.694 --> 32:27.275
Alison, you must have
been terrified.

32:27.446 --> 32:30.358
[ Laughs] Well...
when he stood up at the end,

32:30.533 --> 32:33.775
I'll admit, my bladder and brain
had a momentary disconnect.

32:34.245 --> 32:36.201
Well, our techies should
be able to clear up

32:36.205 --> 32:37.160
picture and sound, but...

32:37.498 --> 32:39.659
I kinda like
the verité quality.

32:40.668 --> 32:43.375
And I wanna build an entire
special around it.

32:44.964 --> 32:48.127
Really? Oh. Okay. Wow.

32:48.300 --> 32:51.258
I am putting you on a plane
to New York tomorrow.

32:51.262 --> 32:53.799
We'll do it in our studio, we'll
bring in some big names.

32:54.098 --> 32:55.804
Are there any journalists
or crime writers

32:55.975 --> 32:57.556
that you are particularly
fond of?

32:57.726 --> 33:00.263
Uh, oh, God. Okay, uh,
lemme think. Um,

33:00.813 --> 33:02.519
Or Dylan? Anybody you can--

33:02.523 --> 33:04.514
We'll-- we'll pipe Dylan in
from here if we need him.

33:04.733 --> 33:06.689
Someone's gotta hold down
the fort, right?

33:06.861 --> 33:09.227
Hey, guys, what about, uh,
going to the police?

33:09.530 --> 33:12.021
You know? I mean, this is a
pretty major break in the case.

33:12.241 --> 33:13.026
It is.

33:13.242 --> 33:15.198
And they can watch it on TV
tomorrow night.

33:15.536 --> 33:16.651
Like the rest of the world.

33:17.121 --> 33:18.156
When we land,

33:18.164 --> 33:19.279
I'm gonna whisk you
to my stylist.

33:19.290 --> 33:20.951
They're gonna do hair, makeup,
wardrobe.

33:21.125 --> 33:23.207
Which you get to keep,
so aim high.

33:40.352 --> 33:42.513
Sarah. Pleasure to meet you,
at last.

33:42.521 --> 33:43.556
Come in. Sit down.

33:44.273 --> 33:46.639
I'm sorry I didn't make it to
your grandmother's memorial.

33:46.817 --> 33:48.227
She and I go way back.

33:48.694 --> 33:52.152
And this mess, well,
it's just a mess, isn't it?

33:52.156 --> 33:53.066
Mr. Mayor...

33:53.073 --> 33:54.859
And our tourism industry
is on life support.

33:55.034 --> 33:57.025
I mean, this is way worse
than a rainy summer.

33:57.203 --> 33:59.194
How about I just ask you what
I came here to ask you?

33:59.580 --> 34:01.491
Ah, big city girl,
straight to the point.

34:01.499 --> 34:03.160
Gotta love it. Shoot.

34:04.126 --> 34:04.956
[ Sighs ]

34:05.211 --> 34:07.327
The police found some VHS tapes
in my house,

34:07.505 --> 34:09.086
and they admitted them
into evidence.

34:09.715 --> 34:10.795
I'd like some copies.

34:11.091 --> 34:12.706
Have you spoken to Chief Vaughn?

34:12.718 --> 34:13.753
I have.

34:13.928 --> 34:17.216
Well, if he says no,
it's a police matter.

34:17.223 --> 34:18.508
It's out of my jurisdiction.
I'm sorry.

34:18.516 --> 34:20.097
Now, if you'll excuse me,
I have to...

34:20.267 --> 34:21.518
How 'bout this for straight
to the point?

34:22.937 --> 34:26.054
You lean on Vaughn and get me
copies of those tapes ASAP

34:26.357 --> 34:27.938
or I tell my husband
the reporter

34:27.942 --> 34:29.523
about your affair
with my grandmother.

34:31.695 --> 34:34.778
I am sure Lisa-Ann Follows
would love to talk

34:34.782 --> 34:37.398
about the sordid love life
of one of The Executioner's

34:37.409 --> 34:39.616
victims and the mayor?

34:40.162 --> 34:41.242
Grandpa.

34:43.374 --> 34:44.864
[ Phone ringing ]

34:48.754 --> 34:49.539
[ Door opening ]

34:52.591 --> 34:54.297
Okay, order whatever you want.

34:54.760 --> 34:57.797
Or just not the champagne.
Not from this joint.

34:58.722 --> 35:01.805
I'll have another double.
No ice.

35:02.518 --> 35:03.928
So...

35:04.436 --> 35:07.052
I just watched a rough cut
of your interview...

35:07.398 --> 35:08.604
Excuse me.

35:09.149 --> 35:12.892
And, ugh, my dear,
for the first time in my life,

35:13.445 --> 35:14.400
I was speechless.

35:14.572 --> 35:16.108
Ah! Awesome.

35:16.574 --> 35:17.814
That is great.

35:18.117 --> 35:18.856
[ Sighs ]

35:20.286 --> 35:21.150
Unbelievable.

35:22.329 --> 35:23.830
Okay. So, um...

35:24.790 --> 35:26.872
Okay, here's something
I've been wanting to ask.

35:26.875 --> 35:27.660
Uh-huh.

35:28.002 --> 35:32.416
How do I translate all of this
into something bigger?

35:33.465 --> 35:34.420
Bigger?

35:34.925 --> 35:36.586
Well, this story's burning
bright for now,

35:36.594 --> 35:37.629
but it won't last forever.

35:37.636 --> 35:39.172
Hell, we're almost out of sins.

35:39.471 --> 35:43.214
Okay. So what exactly
does bigger look like?

35:43.809 --> 35:47.597
Look, I was born in Waterbury,
I spent most of my life here.

35:47.605 --> 35:50.392
God, I rent the apartment
above The Bulletin

35:50.399 --> 35:51.764
because I've sunk
all my life savings

35:51.775 --> 35:53.151
just to keep it on life support.

35:53.694 --> 35:55.059
I refuse to die here.

35:55.237 --> 35:56.818
Not with this albatross
of a newspaper

35:56.822 --> 35:58.062
wrapped around my neck.

36:00.117 --> 36:02.028
Girl to girl?
No bullshit?

36:02.036 --> 36:02.866
Yeah, of course.

36:03.037 --> 36:03.992
Okay.

36:03.996 --> 36:06.078
What you did,
with The Executioner,

36:06.457 --> 36:07.572
balls to the wall.

36:08.417 --> 36:10.078
But he is a pussycat.

36:10.336 --> 36:12.748
People like me,
we have no moral code.

36:13.297 --> 36:14.662
You can't,
not in this business.

36:14.673 --> 36:18.006
And, honey,
underneath all of the bluster,

36:18.761 --> 36:20.376
you're actually kind of nice.

36:22.890 --> 36:23.970
That's not a bad thing.

36:23.974 --> 36:25.805
-It's a good thing, really.
-Mm-hm.

36:30.731 --> 36:32.938
You remember that
News of the World scandal

36:32.941 --> 36:34.522
over in the UK,

36:34.526 --> 36:35.390
where they hacked into
the phone of that

36:35.402 --> 36:36.266
murdered girl's parents?

36:36.445 --> 36:37.400
Of course. What about it?

36:37.613 --> 36:38.398
Well...

36:38.739 --> 36:40.980
let's just say they could have
learned a thing or two from me.

36:42.660 --> 36:44.867
'Cause I was never caught.

36:45.954 --> 36:48.206
Ariel Peterson '5 disappearance
was big news,

36:48.207 --> 36:49.242
or at least for a little while,

36:49.249 --> 36:50.625
but with no new leads,

36:50.626 --> 36:52.287
the story started
to die a slow death.

36:52.294 --> 36:53.500
So...

36:54.630 --> 36:56.996
I made sure it stayed live.

37:00.386 --> 37:02.877
Benny Peterson was
a controlling, jealous man.

37:02.888 --> 37:03.843
Everyone knew it.

37:04.181 --> 37:05.921
He threatened
to kill Heather and Ariel

37:05.933 --> 37:07.514
if Heather ever left him.

37:07.518 --> 37:08.382
All the facts pointed to him,

37:08.394 --> 37:09.804
but there was no
smoking gun.

37:10.938 --> 37:13.554
So I provided one.

37:18.445 --> 37:20.857
Did the trick.
The readership shot up.

37:21.240 --> 37:22.855
Made enough money to keep
The Bulletin afloat

37:22.866 --> 37:23.776
for another year.

37:23.784 --> 37:25.274
Vaughn focused
the entire investigation

37:25.285 --> 37:26.866
on Benny Peterson,

37:26.870 --> 37:29.282
built a compelling case
against him.

37:32.918 --> 37:35.660
And then... Benny hung himself.

37:41.427 --> 37:42.587
Everyone assumed the case
was solved.

37:43.303 --> 37:44.679
Benny killed his daughter,

37:44.680 --> 37:45.760
then he hung himself
out of guilt, but...

37:48.016 --> 37:52.635
Heather... never bought it,
...and I, um...

37:53.272 --> 37:54.182
LISA-ANN: What?

37:55.274 --> 37:56.013
[ Sighs ]

37:56.233 --> 37:58.064
Well, what if I was wrong?

37:58.861 --> 37:59.976
What if Benny was innocent?

38:00.154 --> 38:02.236
What if Ariel's still out there,
and whoever took her...

38:02.781 --> 38:04.567
got away with it because of me?

38:05.033 --> 38:05.863
LISA-AN N: What if?

38:06.577 --> 38:10.240
What if he was guilty, and you
nudged justice along?

38:10.539 --> 38:12.404
[ Rock music playing ]

38:13.083 --> 38:16.450
Tell me, if you could go back,

38:17.129 --> 38:21.213
if you could do things
differently, would you?

38:24.803 --> 38:25.667
[ Sighs ]

38:26.430 --> 38:30.264
Pity won't keep the lights on,
or my staff being paid.

38:32.269 --> 38:35.432
Get this lady a drink.
Pronto!

38:49.161 --> 38:49.991
[ Sighs ]

38:52.039 --> 38:54.280
Sarah, my nose is really itchy.

38:54.291 --> 38:55.531
Don't move.

38:56.752 --> 38:57.662
[ Groans]

38:58.629 --> 39:00.494
It's like I have
poison ivy and...

39:01.089 --> 39:03.000
crabs duking it out
in my left nostril.

39:03.008 --> 39:04.373
-Can I just...?
-No.

39:05.928 --> 39:06.792
[ Sighs ]

39:07.596 --> 39:08.585
If you don't stop moving,

39:08.597 --> 39:10.133
I'm gonna make you look
like a Picasso.

39:11.809 --> 39:13.674
[ Groans ]
I can't. Sorry.

39:13.685 --> 39:14.640
Robin...

39:16.104 --> 39:17.810
ROBIN: What is he doing?

39:18.690 --> 39:20.351
Sarah, come see this.

39:31.954 --> 39:33.410
[ Engine starts ]

39:38.585 --> 39:40.997
ROBIN: Where the hell's
he going?

39:44.424 --> 39:45.709
[ Door opening ]

39:58.021 --> 39:59.727
Sarah, my spidey-senses
are tingling

39:59.731 --> 40:02.814
and telling me that we should
not be doing this.

40:03.026 --> 40:04.482
Wanna just stay in the car?

40:08.073 --> 40:09.108
It's okay, you know.

40:09.658 --> 40:10.738
You don't have to be
brave for me.

40:11.827 --> 40:14.159
I know, but I need to be
brave for Justin.

40:16.456 --> 40:17.662
-Okay?
-Okay.

40:19.126 --> 40:20.366
Let's do this.

40:20.919 --> 40:21.829
Okay.

40:22.087 --> 40:23.327
[ Door opening ]

40:25.090 --> 40:26.330
[ Door closing ]

40:27.259 --> 40:28.499
Which way did he go?

40:28.802 --> 40:29.632
WOMAN: No!

40:29.803 --> 40:31.168
[ Indistinct shouting ]

40:31.555 --> 40:33.261
This way...

40:33.849 --> 40:35.965
WOMAN: Alan, please!
You're scaring me!

40:35.976 --> 40:36.965
ALAN: Just do what I say!

40:37.185 --> 40:38.174
Do it now!

40:38.186 --> 40:39.096
Slow-- slow down.

40:39.104 --> 40:40.435
WOMAN: I can't! Alan!
It's too much!

40:41.148 --> 40:42.137
ALAN: Do it!

40:42.482 --> 40:44.018
[ Groans]

40:45.152 --> 40:47.643
Father, forgive me!
For I have sinned!

40:47.988 --> 40:48.898
[ Groans]

40:48.906 --> 40:50.737
[ Pants ]

40:52.784 --> 40:54.240
Holy shit!

41:00.417 --> 41:01.953
[ Birds chirping ]

41:03.545 --> 41:04.455
[ Chuckles ]
Sure.

41:05.130 --> 41:05.994
Oh, hold on.

41:06.465 --> 41:08.080
The limo's here.

41:10.469 --> 41:12.050
Yeah, no.
It's not a secret.

41:12.054 --> 41:13.794
I've told everyone I'm going.

41:14.181 --> 41:15.466
[ Chuckles ]

41:17.225 --> 41:18.305
Hold on. Wait.

41:19.227 --> 41:20.842
Where's the guy? Okay.

41:22.648 --> 41:25.811
Hello? Jesus.

41:25.984 --> 41:26.939
I don't know
what's happening.

41:27.110 --> 41:29.271
Um, if-- if people can't watch
the special live,

41:29.780 --> 41:32.988
I want those PVRs set, okay?
Make sure.

41:33.951 --> 41:35.691
I've only been to New York
once before,

41:35.702 --> 41:36.657
if you can believe it.

41:36.954 --> 41:38.364
Yep. Years ago.

41:38.372 --> 41:40.112
I'm sure it's changed a lot
since then.

41:40.123 --> 41:41.158
[ Car door closes ]

41:49.466 --> 41:50.967
EXECUTIONER: Hello, Alison.

41:51.593 --> 41:54.335
ALISON: No! No! No! No!

41:55.722 --> 41:58.338
[ Gasps, screams ]

42:07.609 --> 42:11.147
[ Heavy breathing ]

42:25.502 --> 42:28.460
[ Gasps, shuddering breaths ]

42:30.048 --> 42:31.504
No. Please don't do this.

42:33.343 --> 42:36.380
No. No!

42:37.014 --> 42:38.800
[ Whimpers ]

42:39.599 --> 42:41.305
You asked me the other day...

42:42.894 --> 42:44.509
...if I had sinned.

42:44.938 --> 42:45.723
[ Gasps ]

42:46.064 --> 42:49.898
I-- I lied to you. I have
sinned. I am a sinner.

42:49.901 --> 42:51.687
I did something awful,
and I'm sorry.

42:51.695 --> 42:53.686
I'm so sorry.

42:54.906 --> 42:56.771
Oh, God. I'm sorry.

42:56.950 --> 42:57.905
[ Pants ]

42:58.201 --> 43:01.068
But-- But I repent. I repent.

43:01.079 --> 43:02.990
I swear, I'll make up for it.
I will.

43:02.998 --> 43:03.908
I'll do anything.

43:03.915 --> 43:05.246
Please, don't, just--
Please let me go.

43:05.250 --> 43:07.161
Please! No! No!

43:07.335 --> 43:09.621
Let me--!
You can't do this! No!

43:10.881 --> 43:14.544
No!
[ Screams ]

43:17.471 --> 43:19.553
[ Doorbell rings ]

43:21.349 --> 43:22.384
Good morning, Mrs. Bennett.

43:22.601 --> 43:24.091
Uh, hey, Officer Sharma.

43:24.478 --> 43:26.093
Chief Vaughn wanted me
to deliver these.

43:26.438 --> 43:28.679
I guess courier's part
of my job description now.

43:29.066 --> 43:30.021
Thanks!

43:43.371 --> 43:45.282
[ Panting, sexual moans ]

43:54.591 --> 43:58.459
[ Disco music ]

44:02.933 --> 44:04.764
[ Moaning ]

44:15.529 --> 44:18.316
[ Hard rock guitar ]

44:18.657 --> 44:21.444
[ Panting, sexual moans ]

44:34.089 --> 44:38.753
Oh, my God. 15--
Is that Tom?

44:43.682 --> 44:46.014
50, me and the boys, pooling
our money together,

44:46.226 --> 44:48.091
gonna spend all next year
down in the Caribbean.

44:48.812 --> 44:51.019
I got a lead
on a 34-foot monohull.

44:51.022 --> 44:51.886
[ Whistles ]

44:52.274 --> 44:54.515
Figure, you know,
start in Miami,

44:54.901 --> 44:56.482
head south from there.

44:57.154 --> 45:02.148
Cuba, Monserrat, Hispaniola,
Santa Lucia, baby.

45:02.450 --> 45:04.031
Come on, it's gonna be sick.

45:06.204 --> 45:07.444
Yo, Bo,

45:07.998 --> 45:10.990
a side of mayo and some garlic
powder, por favor.

45:12.460 --> 45:15.702
Poor man's garlic aioli!
What? What?

45:23.889 --> 45:25.925
The hell's this?
Calamari?

45:27.893 --> 45:29.053
Whoa!

45:42.741 --> 45:44.322
Whatever's jammed down there
is a whole lot bigger

45:44.326 --> 45:45.111
than an ear.

45:55.921 --> 45:57.001
MAN: Is it Alison?

45:58.465 --> 45:59.375
No comment.

46:00.008 --> 46:02.750
The limo company said
she never got in their car.

46:03.094 --> 46:04.220
She never got on her plane,

46:04.221 --> 46:06.086
she never checked into her
hotel room in New York.

46:06.097 --> 46:08.224
I said, "No comment."

46:08.225 --> 46:09.510
The biblical punishment
for greed

46:10.310 --> 46:11.925
is burning in a vat of hot oil.

46:11.937 --> 46:13.802
This has The Executioner
written all over it.

46:14.064 --> 46:16.680
Are you happy about this?
Is that was this is, huh?

46:17.192 --> 46:19.103
She was your boss.
You knew her!

46:19.277 --> 46:21.893
So you are confirming that
it was Alison Sutherland?

46:24.449 --> 46:26.189
You're a real piece of shit.
You know that?

46:26.201 --> 46:28.442
Maybe. But this is my story,
Vaughn.

46:28.745 --> 46:29.860
Now, you could work with me,

46:29.871 --> 46:31.156
and we can inform
the public together,

46:31.164 --> 46:34.748
or I could do this on my own,
my own way. You choose.

46:36.419 --> 46:40.003
I have the ear and the trust
of this town,

46:40.799 --> 46:41.629
of this country.

46:43.093 --> 46:45.709
Don't think I could say the same
for you, Vaughn!

46:52.269 --> 46:53.805
[ Humming ]

47:03.363 --> 47:04.443
Oh, there you are.

47:04.864 --> 47:06.400
Can I go make you
a nice sandwich?

47:06.408 --> 47:07.739
-I picked up some pastrami.
-No.

47:08.243 --> 47:09.653
You sure?
You must be starving.

47:09.661 --> 47:10.525
I'm fine.

47:21.881 --> 47:23.212
[ Sighs ]

47:51.703 --> 47:52.783
[ Keys jingling ]

47:59.294 --> 48:03.458
GIRL: I tsy bitsy spider
climbed up...

48:05.050 --> 48:10.044
Down came the rain
and washed the spider out

48:10.930 --> 48:14.889
Out came the sun and dried up...

48:15.935 --> 48:18.972
-Hi, Daddy.
-Hey, little man.

48:19.647 --> 48:24.141
Don't stop singing, Ariel.
It's beautiful.

48:25.695 --> 48:31.110
Out came the sun
and dried up all the rain

48:31.451 --> 48:37.242
So the itsy bitsy spider
climbed up the spout again
